1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:05,277
Greetings everyone, this wonderful full moon celebration of November.

2
00:00:07,259 --> 00:00:24,097
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassam

3
00:00:24,888 --> 00:00:34,097
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambhodassa.

4
00:00:34,116 --> 00:00:41,444
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

5
00:00:41,463 --> 00:00:45,347
Well, I'm going to start with a quote from St. Paul.

6
00:00:45,368 --> 00:00:47,570
O death, where is thy sting?

7
00:00:47,969 --> 00:00:50,332
O grave, where is thy victory?

8
00:00:51,093 --> 00:00:53,054
A letter he wrote to the Corinthians.

9
00:00:54,064 --> 00:01:03,502
I was brought up a Roman Catholic and November is a month where the souls in purgatory are remembered.

10
00:01:04,022 --> 00:01:06,466
In Catholic doctrine, there are three realms.

11
00:01:07,087 --> 00:01:07,689
There's hell.

12
00:01:08,129 --> 00:01:09,772
And if you get in there, you're stuck.

13
00:01:10,114 --> 00:01:10,834
There's no way out.

14
00:01:11,736 --> 00:01:14,281
And then there's heaven, which, of course, is very blissful.

15
00:01:14,581 --> 00:01:16,865
And that's where you want to really get stuck.

16
00:01:17,099 --> 00:01:21,730
But there's this sort of in-between place where, well, you weren't that bad in life.

17
00:01:21,852 --> 00:01:23,215
You don't deserve hell.

18
00:01:23,296 --> 00:01:27,286
But on the other hand, you're not sort of clean enough to get into heaven.

19
00:01:27,325 --> 00:01:30,073
You've got to really purify the heart.

20
00:01:30,114 --> 00:01:33,623
So this was the purpose of Purgatory.

21
00:01:33,602 --> 00:01:39,751
Now, in the purgatorial realm, you might suffer just as much as hell, but the distinction is you know the way out.

22
00:01:40,492 --> 00:01:46,361
Now, whether these realms actually exist or not is not important.

23
00:01:46,421 --> 00:01:49,364
They definitely do mirror mental states.

24
00:01:49,965 --> 00:02:00,099
So when you're in hell, in those times when everything falls apart, when the whole world seems to be against you and you don't see a way out, well, that's hell, isn't it?

25
00:02:00,079 --> 00:02:07,085
And we know certain illnesses, certain mental states, driving people, for instance, to suicide.

26
00:02:07,447 --> 00:02:10,368
All these are hellish states.

27
00:02:10,389 --> 00:02:16,155
And heaven, of course, are those wonderful little times when we feel perfectly happy and the world seems to be supporting us.

28
00:02:16,895 --> 00:02:21,500
But I think I can safely say that for most of the time, life is purgatory.

29
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:23,782
And this, of course, is the meaning of dukkha.

30
00:02:24,262 --> 00:02:27,504
It's somehow not entirely satisfactorily.

31
00:02:29,324 --> 00:02:37,340
So in the tradition, in the Roman Catholic tradition, a month was set aside, you see, November.

32
00:02:37,461 --> 00:02:45,175
Now, November doesn't have the color of autumnal October, and it definitely hasn't got the promise of December.

33
00:02:45,758 --> 00:02:48,462
So it's a lovely month, which is dark.

34
00:02:48,443 --> 00:02:50,945
dank, at least in these climes.

35
00:02:51,705 --> 00:03:02,957
And it's devoted, it's a lovely month to devote to thinking about our ancestors, people who died, et cetera, et cetera.

36
00:03:03,799 --> 00:03:04,560
And that we can do.

37
00:03:05,039 --> 00:03:12,108
But I thought this happy idea came to me that this would be a wonderful month every year to contemplate death.

38
00:03:12,707 --> 00:03:15,191
Now, I know you're very excited about that idea.

39
00:03:15,891 --> 00:03:18,213
So we have to begin at the beginning.

40
00:03:18,852 --> 00:03:20,633
And I've written one or two things here, you see.

41
00:03:21,675 --> 00:03:30,343
So when we talk about the beginning of time, we're not talking really, I'm not talking here about time in the past, you know, when time began.

42
00:03:30,383 --> 00:03:34,146
I'm talking about every single moment of consciousness.

43
00:03:34,266 --> 00:03:48,842
Just in that absolute moment of beginning, we become, we fall into an identity of what it is we're actually experiencing, which is, of course, through this psychophysical organism.

44
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:55,067
And herein, just in this understanding, is the fear of death.

45
00:03:55,627 --> 00:04:08,826
Right there, at the end point of that consciousness, is the letting go of a moment of being awake, and that point there is the point of death.

46
00:04:09,207 --> 00:04:18,541
Unfortunately, these series of conscious moments are so quick that they all seem to run together, giving us an impression of continuity.

47
00:04:18,521 --> 00:04:24,307
And of course, in that moment, too, there is also the destruction of fear.

48
00:04:26,209 --> 00:04:32,394
Now, the Buddha tells us that the contemplation of death is the most powerful of all contemplations.

49
00:04:33,375 --> 00:04:42,403
But we are actually reaching down to the very foundation stone of our delusion, this delusion of identity, the delusion of self.

50
00:04:42,423 --> 00:04:48,310
And if there's one thing that the self does not want to do is it does not want to die.

51
00:04:48,947 --> 00:04:51,031
And here he is, this is what he says about it.

52
00:04:53,473 --> 00:05:02,466
Disciples, mindfulness of death, when developed and pursued, is of great fruit and great benefit.

53
00:05:03,767 --> 00:05:07,552
It gains a footing in nibbana, the deathless.

54
00:05:08,533 --> 00:05:12,540
Has nibbana, the deathless, as its final end?

55
00:05:13,821 --> 00:05:18,026
Nibbana here is, of course, that transcendent dimension.

56
00:05:18,648 --> 00:05:19,870
What's he actually saying here?

57
00:05:20,252 --> 00:05:32,706
He's saying that if we really contemplate this whole idea of death, this notion of death that we have, we will get a glimpse of what nibbana actually is.

58
00:05:32,786 --> 00:05:34,632
That's the footing, a glimpse.

59
00:05:35,336 --> 00:05:46,870
And if we continue to do it, this path alone, I mean, this is what he's saying, just the contemplation of death will actually bring us to the end of dukkha, the end of suffering, right?

60
00:05:47,211 --> 00:05:58,002
And it'll be done at that point where that whole notion, that whole concept of self completely disappears, okay?

61
00:05:59,923 --> 00:06:02,906
Now, I do mention a book here by Franz Becker.

62
00:06:03,646 --> 00:06:06,589
It's called The Denial of Death that was written in 1973.

63
00:06:07,050 --> 00:06:12,716
And it is still a smashing read and well worth buying and having a look at it.

64
00:06:13,456 --> 00:06:28,529
And what he says is the basic motivation of human behavior is our biological need to control our basic anxiety, to deny the terror of death.

65
00:06:28,898 --> 00:06:30,341
Now that says it perfectly.

66
00:06:30,781 --> 00:06:34,788
I'll repeat that because it's such a, you know, it gets it straight on.

67
00:06:35,449 --> 00:06:47,632
The basic motivation for human behavior is our biological need, physical need to control our basic anxiety.

68
00:06:48,187 --> 00:06:50,110
to deny the terror of death.

69
00:06:50,690 --> 00:07:00,264
And that's exactly leads us to those three basic attitudes that come out of that delusion of believing we are this body, heart and mind.

70
00:07:01,045 --> 00:07:04,550
The one is, of course, gathering, acquiring.

71
00:07:04,610 --> 00:07:09,637
The more we have more money, more power, more riches, the more safe we feel.

72
00:07:09,617 --> 00:07:12,420
Safety, that's what we're searching for, safety.

73
00:07:12,980 --> 00:07:18,987
And of course, if anything undermines that, then they become the enemy, the rivals, the enemy.

74
00:07:19,007 --> 00:07:20,668
We've got to get rid of them.

75
00:07:20,689 --> 00:07:23,031
And if they happen to be bigger than us, we've got to run.

76
00:07:24,052 --> 00:07:36,603
So these three fundamental attitudes of acquisitiveness, fear, and aversion are coming out of that fundamental delusion of self.

77
00:07:38,879 --> 00:07:42,545
And I like it when he says it's a biological, it's a physical need, right?

78
00:07:42,564 --> 00:07:44,947
Because, you know, without a body, you're not here.

79
00:07:45,209 --> 00:07:48,052
So this fear roots itself in the body.

80
00:07:50,216 --> 00:07:55,524
Now, here's the Buddha asking his monks, well, how often should we meditate on death?

81
00:07:55,543 --> 00:08:02,415
So on one occasion, this is paraphrased, on one occasion, the Buddha asked several monks, how often do you contemplate death?

82
00:08:02,435 --> 00:08:05,418
And one of them replied, well, I contemplate death every day, Lord.

83
00:08:06,019 --> 00:08:07,182
They said, that's not good enough.

84
00:08:07,651 --> 00:08:10,898
And then he asked another monk and he said, how often do you contemplate death?

85
00:08:11,598 --> 00:08:15,867
He said, well, I contemplate death with each mouthful I eat during a meal.

86
00:08:16,288 --> 00:08:17,271
It's not good enough.

87
00:08:18,252 --> 00:08:20,478
And then he turned around to another and he said, what about you?

88
00:08:20,538 --> 00:08:25,487
And he said, well, I contemplate death with each in-breath and out-breath.

89
00:08:25,507 --> 00:08:28,814
And the Buddha smiled and he was pleased, you see.

90
00:08:30,382 --> 00:08:34,268
So, of course, we can't be always thinking about death all the time.

91
00:08:34,707 --> 00:08:36,070
I mean, completely all the time.

92
00:08:36,410 --> 00:08:41,197
But as you know, in medieval times, death was very obvious.

93
00:08:41,298 --> 00:08:43,841
I mean, people died in front of you, you know.

94
00:08:45,624 --> 00:08:48,187
And they always and they had they always kept death.

95
00:08:49,248 --> 00:09:00,908
It was a habit to keep a memento mori, a reminder of death, which was normally some sort of little skull or something, kept on a table by the bedside or whatever it could be easily seen.

96
00:09:00,967 --> 00:09:04,013
So you could catch your eye and it would just come up just that moment.

97
00:09:04,033 --> 00:09:06,937
You know, there is an end to my life.

98
00:09:08,379 --> 00:09:14,309
And every day shortens the period by where I'm going to actually reach this point.

99
00:09:15,774 --> 00:09:22,009
So that's, now, when we're thinking about the actual moment of death, that's all it is, isn't it?

100
00:09:22,649 --> 00:09:30,527
You could be shocked, you know, somebody could throw you under a bus, for instance, and just in that shocking moment, you'd be breathing in, wouldn't you?

101
00:09:30,547 --> 00:09:31,489
And then you'd be dead.

102
00:09:31,942 --> 00:09:35,846
On the other hand, you could be just breathing out, you know, just your last breath.

103
00:09:36,287 --> 00:09:37,609
You could just letting go.

104
00:09:37,629 --> 00:09:40,491
And at the end of the out-breath, there's death.

105
00:09:40,532 --> 00:09:52,826
So every time you're sitting in meditation, just knowing that the in-breath ends and the out-breath ends is to keep us in touch with the idea that everything vanishes.

106
00:09:53,006 --> 00:09:54,187
Everything comes to an end.

107
00:09:54,668 --> 00:09:56,150
And this body will die.

108
00:09:56,191 --> 00:09:58,033
This person will die.

109
00:10:02,840 --> 00:10:12,375
And of course, if we keep constantly distracting ourselves, always finding something to do, something to achieve, something, you know, we're just going to be taken by surprise.

110
00:10:14,820 --> 00:10:17,224
I mean, what would our last thoughts be?

111
00:10:17,283 --> 00:10:19,447
I mean, just consider, just consider.

112
00:10:20,625 --> 00:10:31,706
You're sitting at breakfast there and you're holding a piece of toast and it's saturated, dripping with hot butter and layers of marmalade.

113
00:10:31,726 --> 00:10:36,215
And as you raise it to your mouth, suddenly you have a heart attack.

114
00:10:36,235 --> 00:10:37,857
Can you imagine the agony?

115
00:10:38,833 --> 00:10:39,895
What would you do?

116
00:10:40,216 --> 00:10:52,842
Would you would you go for a final bite or would you sit there calmly, knowing and just letting that toast drop and falling away into death?

117
00:10:54,173 --> 00:11:12,394
Now, on the other hand, we have a story of a Zen monk, it's only an apocryphal story, falling over a cliff, hanging on by his nails for dear life and having the time to admire, sneaking from a cranny, a little wildflower.

118
00:11:12,414 --> 00:11:13,917
That's how we want to go, isn't it?

119
00:11:13,937 --> 00:11:16,980
Calm, peaceful, with joy in our hearts.

120
00:11:17,380 --> 00:11:18,582
Why not?

121
00:11:18,602 --> 00:11:18,763
Why not?

122
00:11:20,667 --> 00:11:22,629
The Buddha says there are four types of people.

123
00:11:22,669 --> 00:11:30,841
There are those who wake up to death, who wake up to the idea of death, the immediacy of death.

124
00:11:32,663 --> 00:11:35,388
Even upon hearing the word very early on in life.

125
00:11:35,869 --> 00:11:39,072
And there are those who don't wake up until someone dear to them dies.

126
00:11:39,594 --> 00:11:43,840
I remember when my mother and father died, I went, I was telling the family that I'm next.

127
00:11:46,115 --> 00:11:48,539
And there are those who wake up when lots of people die.

128
00:11:48,639 --> 00:11:59,822
So, I mean, you know, this whole catastrophe that's happened around COVID with people dying here and there in that first wave, you know, that really created a lot of fear and anxiety in society.

129
00:12:03,089 --> 00:12:05,153
And the final one, of course, is when...

130
00:12:05,892 --> 00:12:13,845
or the worst case scenario is to suddenly wake up to the whole notion of death when the doctor tells you you've got six weeks to live.

131
00:12:14,306 --> 00:12:18,352
I go, that's called being unprepared for a terminal shock.

132
00:12:19,975 --> 00:12:28,068
So, but no matter how ready we are for death, it'll always come with a shock.

133
00:12:28,488 --> 00:12:36,625
Because so long as the self is there, there's always that residue, no matter how small, of fear.

134
00:12:39,236 --> 00:12:50,631
But now that we've got this war right on our doorstep, and of course the war's going on all over the place, consider the soldier, what he must have to brace himself for.

135
00:12:51,172 --> 00:12:57,019
He goes in with his machine gun and whatnot, but I mean, he knows that he could be shot.

136
00:12:57,620 --> 00:13:04,889
So there's always that wonderful ability to be able to be open to the idea that you're going to die.

137
00:13:05,139 --> 00:13:15,504
And it's one of those things I think that a soldier who goes in with proper intention has the ability to turn it into a spiritual practice.

138
00:13:18,572 --> 00:13:20,235
Anyway, how do we do it?

139
00:13:20,296 --> 00:13:21,418
So this is the big question, isn't it?

140
00:13:21,817 --> 00:13:24,982
How do we actually do this contemplation on death?

141
00:13:25,464 --> 00:13:29,029
Now, contemplation is not the same as thinking, right?

142
00:13:29,450 --> 00:13:32,355
We're not going to sit here thinking about death.

143
00:13:32,434 --> 00:13:33,216
What is death?

144
00:13:33,417 --> 00:13:34,197
What does it mean?

145
00:13:34,258 --> 00:13:35,600
Where is it going?

146
00:13:36,140 --> 00:13:37,663
What will happen to me when I die?

147
00:13:38,283 --> 00:13:41,529
That's a complete waste of time.

148
00:13:41,549 --> 00:13:44,934
What we're going to do is to...

149
00:13:45,251 --> 00:13:47,336
Use a phrase, use a mantra.

150
00:13:48,298 --> 00:13:56,274
You can choose a passage, you know, but anything which brings up the feelings, the attitudes we have around death.

151
00:13:57,296 --> 00:14:07,075
And as we repeat these phrases, we're getting in touch with the resistance, not wanting to accept the truth value of it.

152
00:14:07,307 --> 00:14:15,059
You know, and it's being able to keep on saying it, keep on saying it gently into the heart until you get that surrender.

153
00:14:15,640 --> 00:14:23,572
And then there's that digestion that comes into the heart of the whole idea of sickness, aging and death.

154
00:14:24,354 --> 00:14:27,158
Sickness, of course, is a is a prelude to death.

155
00:14:27,557 --> 00:14:31,965
And aging is just a slow, miserable death, which.

156
00:14:32,332 --> 00:14:41,005
which I'm in, which I am now coming to on, such as myself.

157
00:14:41,025 --> 00:15:01,496
And as we practice this, and that sort of openness comes to that, and we surrender to the truth of that, you might find that there's a sort of sense of wonderful relief, and even a smile appears on the face.

158
00:15:02,388 --> 00:15:10,876
And then there's that ability to hold it with a gentle kindness, with a gentle kindness.

159
00:15:15,422 --> 00:15:17,984
And there's always that sense of humor about it.

160
00:15:18,004 --> 00:15:19,785
I mean, the whole situation is ridiculous.

161
00:15:19,806 --> 00:15:23,330
You get born, you do all this work and then you drop dead.

162
00:15:23,649 --> 00:15:29,897
If you remember the old comedian joke, life's hard and then you die.

163
00:15:30,636 --> 00:15:36,844
Samuel Beckett says it beautifully in his own inimitable way.

164
00:15:37,264 --> 00:15:39,626
We are born astride a grave.

165
00:15:41,970 --> 00:15:47,596
OK, so what I'm going to do is give you these sentences.

166
00:15:47,856 --> 00:15:53,943
And what you do is just repeat them gently within your heart.

167
00:15:54,312 --> 00:15:57,456
We're going to do it for about a good half minute each.

168
00:15:58,658 --> 00:16:07,350
It sounds long, but you'd be surprised how quickly it passes.

169
00:16:07,390 --> 00:16:13,941
So first of all, there's the sickness, which is a sort of preparation for death.

170
00:16:14,932 --> 00:16:17,577
You can look upon it as a preparation for death.

171
00:16:17,719 --> 00:16:20,703
The body manifesting its vulnerability.

172
00:16:21,306 --> 00:16:25,433
So there's discomfort or pain and there's always some disability.

173
00:16:25,774 --> 00:16:36,115
And this contemplation undermines this intoxication with youth of always trying to stay young, of always being 60 as the new 40, things like that.

174
00:16:37,124 --> 00:16:39,566
So sickness is unpreventable.

175
00:16:39,706 --> 00:16:45,192
The body is going to fall sick to some degree or another in our lifetimes.

176
00:16:45,892 --> 00:16:48,455
Hopefully, of course, it will be something which passes.

177
00:16:49,115 --> 00:16:52,639
So these are the three sentences.

178
00:16:52,719 --> 00:16:54,541
The body is subject to disease.

179
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:56,923
The body is of a nature to fall ill.

180
00:16:57,363 --> 00:16:59,846
This body has not gone beyond sickness.

181
00:17:00,907 --> 00:17:06,692
So I'll say them again and then I'll create a break for you to just keep repeating it.

182
00:17:09,355 --> 00:17:10,676
Let's see if I can...

183
00:17:15,462 --> 00:17:15,563
Okay.

184
00:17:15,583 --> 00:17:17,925
This body is subject to disease.

185
00:17:22,612 --> 00:17:24,755
Repeating it gently into the heart.

186
00:17:25,154 --> 00:17:28,680
This body is subject to disease.

187
00:17:37,417 --> 00:17:40,565
This body is of a nature to fall ill.

188
00:17:52,412 --> 00:17:55,578
This body has not gone beyond sickness.

189
00:18:04,232 --> 00:18:08,818
The next set of phrases are to do with aging, which is, of course, as I say, a progressive dying.

190
00:18:09,579 --> 00:18:17,790
This undermines the obsession with health and beauty, with intolerances and fasting and food ingredients.

191
00:18:18,071 --> 00:18:19,713
It's the obsession with it all.

192
00:18:21,415 --> 00:18:23,960
So aging, of course, is inevitable.

193
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:28,425
So again, the three phrases, this body is subject to aging.

194
00:18:29,026 --> 00:18:30,969
This body has not gone beyond aging.

195
00:18:31,390 --> 00:18:33,952
This body is now in the process of aging.

196
00:18:35,147 --> 00:18:50,525
So again, we just repeat these phrases into our hearts, observing any resistance, feeling the resistance, just allowing the resistance to manifest and wait for it to die until we surrender to the truth of the statement.

197
00:18:52,926 --> 00:18:55,230
This body is subject to disease.

198
00:19:00,515 --> 00:19:04,799
This body is subject, this body has not gone beyond aging.

199
00:19:08,829 --> 00:19:14,939
This body is now in a process of aging.

200
00:19:16,760 --> 00:19:19,986
Life is uncertain, death is certain.

201
00:19:21,827 --> 00:19:31,221
This contemplation undermines the overwhelming clinging to life at all costs, shoring it up, barricading it with fame, riches, and power.

202
00:19:33,023 --> 00:19:34,586
It is inescapable.

203
00:19:36,048 --> 00:19:37,790
Everyone must die.

204
00:19:37,957 --> 00:19:41,539
The remainder of our lifespan is decreasing continually.

205
00:19:42,641 --> 00:19:48,306
Death will come regardless of whether or not we have made time to practice Dharma.

206
00:19:49,847 --> 00:19:53,131
We don't know when we are going to die.

207
00:19:54,132 --> 00:19:55,873
These are all phrases from the Buddha.

208
00:19:55,893 --> 00:19:57,634
We don't know when we're going to die.

209
00:19:58,435 --> 00:20:00,998
Human life expectancy is uncertain.

210
00:20:01,278 --> 00:20:05,382
There are many causes of death and the human body is fragile.

211
00:20:06,626 --> 00:20:10,710
Only the practice of Dharma can help us at the time of death.

212
00:20:11,911 --> 00:20:13,333
Our wealth cannot help us.

213
00:20:13,752 --> 00:20:15,473
Our loved ones cannot help us.

214
00:20:16,275 --> 00:20:17,957
Our own body cannot help us.

215
00:20:18,957 --> 00:20:20,898
Death is inescapable.

216
00:20:22,059 --> 00:20:25,542
These are the phrases to repeat.

217
00:20:25,563 --> 00:20:27,744
This body is subject to disease.

218
00:20:28,746 --> 00:20:30,787
This body has not gone beyond.

219
00:20:31,428 --> 00:20:33,108
This body is subject to death.

220
00:20:34,529 --> 00:20:36,432
This body has not gone beyond death.

221
00:20:37,119 --> 00:20:39,102
This body will die.

222
00:20:43,047 --> 00:20:49,714
There is a final contemplation which links into this, which is about karma.

223
00:20:49,994 --> 00:20:53,057
And it's recognizing that we own our actions.

224
00:20:54,819 --> 00:20:57,564
We inherit the results of our actions.

225
00:20:58,505 --> 00:21:02,128
We are born because of our actions into every moment.

226
00:21:03,009 --> 00:21:05,692
We're related through our actions.

227
00:21:06,854 --> 00:21:10,038
And we are live dependent upon my actions.

228
00:21:10,058 --> 00:21:14,265
So whatever good or ill I do, I shall inherit the results.

229
00:21:14,644 --> 00:21:16,907
That's a nice little thing just to repeat.

230
00:21:19,172 --> 00:21:23,999
Having done these exercises, you might think, oh, well, OK, so I get a footing in Nibbana.

231
00:21:24,318 --> 00:21:27,083
I might get a little hint of what Nibbana actually is.

232
00:21:27,123 --> 00:21:31,950
And if I do it often enough and with real sincerity, I might even be liberated.

233
00:21:32,452 --> 00:21:33,193
But is that all?

234
00:21:33,233 --> 00:21:34,515
Not at all.

235
00:21:34,596 --> 00:21:42,925
There are amazing benefits to be had right through this practice of contemplation.

236
00:21:43,866 --> 00:21:48,972
First of all, there's that relief that comes from the acceptance of the inevitable.

237
00:21:49,153 --> 00:21:50,855
We simply stop fighting.

238
00:21:51,915 --> 00:21:55,461
So much energy is lost, pushing thoughts and feelings away.

239
00:21:55,480 --> 00:21:59,945
This energy is now released in order to do better things with it.

240
00:22:01,089 --> 00:22:06,518
The underlying fear of sickness, aging and death puts a pall over our lives.

241
00:22:06,538 --> 00:22:08,299
Now life becomes more colourful.

242
00:22:08,701 --> 00:22:10,002
We appreciate it more.

243
00:22:10,303 --> 00:22:14,528
We regain some of the childlike wonder of the miracle of life.

244
00:22:15,190 --> 00:22:19,977
It's as though somebody's pulled up a blind in a room that we didn't think was dark.

245
00:22:22,201 --> 00:22:24,143
Now, with this, there comes gratitude.

246
00:22:24,624 --> 00:22:36,659
And from out of that gratitude, a desire to share our joys and comfort others, share our joys with others, to share our joys and to comfort others in their sorrow.

247
00:22:38,961 --> 00:22:45,609
Accepting death as part of the life cycle, we're more at ease by someone's dying bedside.

248
00:22:46,180 --> 00:23:00,707
And it brings sharply into the present, it brings us sharply into the present, to the arising and passing away of every moment, and to the realization that within all this change is the unchangeable, the unconditioned, the beatitude of nibbana.

249
00:23:01,788 --> 00:23:09,403
So that is why in avipassana we investigate anicca, impermanence, one of the three characteristics of existence.

250
00:23:09,755 --> 00:23:18,986
It leads to the realization that it reads, it makes us realize that to hold on to anything is illusory and bound to bring some level of dissatisfaction.

251
00:23:19,686 --> 00:23:29,199
And it leads us to realize the insubstantiality of the self, once so solid, but now just arising and passing away with every moment of consciousness.

252
00:23:30,200 --> 00:23:36,488
So you'll find lots of books if you want to find them somewhere.

253
00:23:38,357 --> 00:23:39,881
There are writers.

254
00:23:42,585 --> 00:23:44,848
So what's the practice in daily life?

255
00:23:44,868 --> 00:23:50,159
Well, it's putting aside just a few moments in the morning.

256
00:23:50,179 --> 00:23:54,246
You could do it just after the sitting, before metta.

257
00:23:55,086 --> 00:23:56,690
It's nice to do before metta, I think.

258
00:23:58,192 --> 00:24:01,699
In which you just repeat those phrases gently into your heart.

259
00:24:02,454 --> 00:24:05,939
And these sorts of contemplations work over time.

260
00:24:06,599 --> 00:24:09,443
They're not something that just works because you've done it once.

261
00:24:09,943 --> 00:24:15,570
Even if you were to do it all day, which would be a good idea, the effect would disappear.

262
00:24:15,691 --> 00:24:22,138
It has to be done every day, all day, every day, for every day of our lives.

263
00:24:22,759 --> 00:24:24,021
Just that little reminder.

264
00:24:24,643 --> 00:24:28,146
And it is a really powerful practice.

265
00:24:29,188 --> 00:24:30,690
So...

266
00:24:30,906 --> 00:24:33,290
I want to leave you with a little film.

267
00:24:33,471 --> 00:24:44,170
It's not a very good quality at all, but it does get across the inevitable and the shortness, the shortness of our life.

268
00:24:44,230 --> 00:24:49,199
We don't realize how short it is until we get until we until it's nearly over.

269
00:24:49,779 --> 00:24:53,606
But it's amazing how time passes and it does.

270
00:24:53,671 --> 00:25:14,311
I can only hope that, and I have not, I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance, that it has not caused confusion, and that by your daily practice of the contemplation of aging, sickness, and death will lead you to your liberation sooner rather than later.

